{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Kadeem Harris | image = Kadeem Harris (2).jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Harris playing for [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in 2016. | fullname = Kadeem Raymond Mathurin-Harris<ref name="Professional retain list & free transfers 2012/13">{{Cite news |title=Professional retain list & free transfers 2012/13 |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0,,10794~179534,00.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012034401/http://www.football-league.co.uk/staticFiles/4e/bd/0%2C%2C10794~179534%2C00.pdf |archivedate=12 October 2013 |publisher=The Football League |format=PDF |date=18 May 2013 |page=11 |accessdate=30 July 2013 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1993|6|8|df=y}}<ref name="Hugman2010–11 188">{{Cite book |title=The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2010–11 |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-84596-601-0 |editor-last=Hugman |editor-first=Barry J. |page=188}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Westminster]], England | height = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name="Hugman2010–11 188" /> | position = [[Midfielder]] | currentclub = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] | clubnumber = 23 | youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}–2009 | youthclubs1 = [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] | years1 = 2009–2012 | clubs1 = [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] | caps1 = 19 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2012– | clubs2 = [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] | caps2 = 69 | goals2 = 6 | years3 = 2013 | clubs3 = → [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] (loan) | caps3 = 10 | goals3 = 1 | years4 = 2015 | clubs4 = → [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] (loan) | caps4 = 11 | goals4 = 0 | club-update = 21:50, 29 January 2019 (UTC) }} '''Kadeem Raymond Mathurin-Harris''' (born 8 June 1993), known as '''Kadeem Harris''', is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Premier League]] club [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], as a [[midfielder]].
==Career==
===Early career=== Born in [[Westminster]], London,<ref name="Hugman2010–11 188" /> Harris once held the record for the youngest player ever to appear for Wycombe in the [[Football League]], breaking [[Ikechi Anya]]'s record set in 2004 by coming on as a substitute for the final 12 minutes against [[Yeovil Town F.C.|Yeovil Town]] in December 2009, aged 16 years and 201 days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wycombewanderers.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10430~1915891,00.html|title=HARRIS: "I'M OVER THE MOON"|last=|first=|date=29 December 2009|work=|access-date=13 April 2011|publisher=Wycombe Wanderers F.C}}</ref>
===Wycombe Wanderers=== Harris made his home debut for the club against [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] on the last day of the [[2009–10 Wycombe Wanderers F.C. season|2009–10]] season.<ref name="Games played by Kadeem Harris in 2009/2010" /> He found his chances for first team football limited in the [[2010–11 Wycombe Wanderers F.C. season|2010–11]] season, only featuring for 25 minutes in the [[Football League Trophy]] tie with [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]].<ref name="Games played by Kadeem Harris in 2010/2011" /> He scored his first goal for the first team in the quarter-final of the [[Berks & Bucks Senior Cup]] against [[Burnham F.C.|Burnham]]. Harris was awarded the [[Football League Two|League Two]] Apprentice of the Year at the Football League Awards in April 2011 and later that month was one of four Wycombe scholars to be awarded professional contracts by the club.<ref name="AOTY">{{Cite news |url=http://www.wycombewanderers.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10430~2320659,00.html |title=Harris Wins League Award |date=1 April 2011 |access-date=13 April 2011 |publisher=Wycombe Wanderers F.C}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Four sign Wycombe Wanderers pro contracts|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/13051517.stm| work=BBC Sport| date=12 April 2011| accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref> Harris was subject to a £50,000 bid by [[Premier League]] side [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in July 2011 but the offer was rejected by Wycombe.<ref>{{cite news |title=Waddock confirms Harris bid|url=http://www.bucksfreepress.co.uk/sport/localsport/9124965.Waddock_confirms_Harris_bid/| publisher=Bucks Free Press| date=6 July 2011| accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> Harris made a late cameo appearance on the first day of the [[2011–12 Wycombe Wanderers F.C. season|2011–12]] season against [[Scunthorpe United F.C.|Scunthorpe United]], replacing [[Joel Grant]].<ref name="Games played by Kadeem Harris in 2011/2012" /> He then made his first start in a competitive match for Wycombe in the [[League Cup]] during Wycombe's clash with [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] on 9 August 2011.<ref name="Games played by Kadeem Harris in 2011/2012" /> Wycombe won on penalties but the game also saw Harris' record as youngest player broken by Jordon Ibe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wycombewanderers.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/LatestNews/0,,10430~2415846,00.html|title=Wycombe Wanderers {{!}} News {{!}} Latest News {{!}} Latest News {{!}} JORDAN SETS NEW CLUB RECORD|website=www.wycombewanderers.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com|access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref> On 24 September 2011, Harris made his first league start for club in a 1–0 win over [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wycombe 1–0 Sheffield Utd|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14958080.stm|work=BBC Sport|date=24 September 2011|accessdate=28 September 2011}}</ref> He was a first team regular and 22 appearances during the first half of the 2011–12 season,<ref name="Games played by Kadeem Harris in 2011/2012" /> before departing the club in January 2012.<ref name="JoinsCardiff" /> Harris made 26 appearances in all competitions for Wycombe and scored no goals.<ref name="Soccerbase" />
===Cardiff City=== [[File:Kadeem Harris 1.png|thumb|right|Harris playing for the [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] [[Cardiff City F.C. Academy#Development Squad|Development Squad]] in 2013.]] On 30 January 2012, Harris signed for [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] on a three-and-half-year contract for an undisclosed fee.<ref name="JoinsCardiff">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cardiffcity.co.uk.p.preprod.performgroup.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10335~2593968,00.html |title=Kadeem Harris joins Cardiff City |date=30 January 2012 |access-date=30 January 2012 |publisher=Cardiff City F.C}}</ref> His maiden call up to the first team came in a 3–1 league defeat to [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]] on 4 February 2012, when he was an unused substitute.<ref name="ESPNFC1112">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/142244/kadeem-harris?season=2011 |title=Kadeem Harris Player Profile – ESPN FC |website=www.espnfc.com |access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref> He was an unused substitute on a further three occasions during the [[2011–12 Cardiff City F.C. season|2011–12]] season and was not called into the squad for the [[2012 Football League play-offs#Championship|playoffs]] or the [[2012 Football League Cup Final|2012 League Cup final]].<ref name="ESPNFC1112" /> Harris was only called into the first team squad on one occasion during the [[2012–13 Cardiff City F.C. season|2012–13]] Championship-winning season, when he made his debut in a 2–1 [[FA Cup]] third round defeat against [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]] on 5 January 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/142244/kadeem-harris?season=2012|title=Kadeem Harris Player Profile – ESPN FC|website=www.espnfc.com|access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref> Harris started the match and was substituted for [[Tommy O'Sullivan]] after 64 minutes.<ref name="Games played by Kadeem Harris in 2012/2013" /> Harris received his first call into the first team squad of the [[2013–14 Cardiff City F.C. season|2013–14]] season on 28 August 2013, when he was an unused substitute for a 2–0 League Cup first round win over [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]].<ref name="ESPNFC1314">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/142244/kadeem-harris?season=2013 |title=Kadeem Harris Player Profile – ESPN FC |website=www.espnfc.com |access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref> He was again an unused substitute in the following round, which saw Cardiff lose 3–2 to fellow Premier League side [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref name="ESPNFC1314" />
====Loans Spells==== After putting in an "outstanding" performance for Cardiff in a [[Professional Development League]] game versus [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brentfordfc.co.uk/news/article/cardiff-city-ds-v-brentford-ds-14.10.13-1112867.aspx|title=CARDIFF CITY DS 3 BRENTFORD DS 1|author=Chris Wickham|work=brentfordfc.co.uk|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref> on 18 October 2013 Harris joined the [[League One]] side on a loan running until 5 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/24581153|title=Kadeem Harris: Brentford sign Cardiff winger on loan|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref> The following day, he was included in the squad to face [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]] and after replacing [[Will Grigg]] on 65 minutes, he scored the first senior goal of his career in a 3–1 win.<ref name=":1" /> Harris scored his second Brentford goal in an FA Cup first round tie against local neighbours [[Staines Town F.C.|Staines Town]] on 9 November, scoring the second in a 5–0 victory.<ref name=":1" /> Harris was stretchered off with a hamstring problem in a 3–0 victory over [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 21 December, casting doubt on his loan being extended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/on-loan-cardiff-city-winger-suffers-6439041|title=On-loan Cardiff City winger suffers injury blow against Preston|author=Matt Lewis|date=21 December 2013|work=getwestlondon|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref> On 26 December it was reported that Harris would be out for a month, with manager [[Mark Warburton]] keen on extending the loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/bees-plan-extend-loan-injured-6447109|title=Bees plan to extend the loan of injured Cardiff City youngster|author=Jacob Murtagh|date=26 December 2013|work=getwestlondon|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref> Harris [[Twitter|tweeted]] on 29 December that he would be returning to Cardiff, leaving plans to extend his loan up in the air.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/KadeemHarris27/status/417359585759199232|title=Kads|work=Twitter|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref> Harris made 11 appearances for Brentford and scored two goals.<ref name="Soccerbase">{{Cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=52670 |title=Kadeem Harris – Football Stats – Cardiff City – Age 22 – Soccer Base |website=soccerbase.com |access-date=31 October 2015}}</ref> It was reported in mid-March 2014 that Harris was close to a return to the Bees to cover for the injured [[Sam Saunders (footballer)|Sam Saunders]], despite being sidelined with an ankle injury himself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/brentford-ponder-swoop-cardiff-city-6803302|title=Brentford ponder swoop for Cardiff City winger|author=Jacob Murtagh|date=12 March 2014|work=getwestlondon|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref>
The following season, Harris started to become a regular under new manager, [[Russell Slade]], who was appointed in October.<ref name="Soccerbase1415" /> He played his first league game for Cardiff in a 5–3 loss to [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]], on 20 December.<ref name="Soccerbase1415" /> Harris scored his first goal for ''The Bluebirds'' in a [[FA Cup]] win against [[Colchester United F.C.|Colchester United]], following this with his first league goal against [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]].<ref name="Soccerbase1415" />
On 22 August 2015, Harris joined [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] on loan until 21 November 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Loan Deal: Harris links up with Tykes|url=http://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/article/loan-deal-harris-links-up-with-tykes-2638055.aspx|publisher=Cardiff City|date=22 August 2015|accessdate=22 August 2015}}</ref> He made his debut in a goalless draw against [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] and went onto make 14 appearances for Barnsley before returning to Cardiff.<ref name="Soccerbase1516" />
===Return to first team=== In August 2016, Harris received a lot of praise from Cardiff fans and manager, [[Paul Trollope]], after his performances against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] and [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in an unusual [[right wing back]] position.<ref>{{cite news |title=Why Kadeem Harris has played his way into contention for a starting spot as Cardiff City youngsters lead the way |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kadeem-harris-played-way-contention-11779342 |work=South Wales Echo |first=Phil |last=Smith |date=21 August 2016 |accessdate=21 August 2016}}</ref> Harris continued to impress under new manager, [[Neil Warnock]] and eventually found his first goal on 14 January, scoring in the [[Severnside derby]] against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] in a 3–2 win.<ref name="Soccerbase1617" /> He followed this by scoring two to help Cardiff come back from 2 goals down to beat [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], 4–3, before scoring his third in two games against [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]].<ref name="Soccerbase1617" />
His performance throughout the season saw Harris gifted the number 11 shirt for the 2017–18 season.<ref>{{cite news |title=2017/18 Squad Numbers Confirmed! |url=https://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/201718-squad-numbers-confirmed/ |publisher=Cardiff City Official Site |date=2 August 2017 |accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref> However, an ankle injury suffered during pre-season ruled him out for 3 months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kadeem Harris sidelined for up to three months with Cardiff City star needing ankle surgery |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/kadeem-harris-sidelined-up-three-13431376 |work=South Wales Echo |date=4 August 2017 |accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> Following several games for the under-23 side, Harris eventually made his return to the first team in a 0–0 draw at [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], replacing [[Junior Hoilett]].<ref name="Soccerbase1718" />
Harris scored his first goal since returning from injury in the [[2018–19 Cardiff City F.C. season|2018–19 season]], in a 4–2 win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in the [[Premier League]], Cardiff's first win of the campaign.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cardiff City 4–2 Fulham |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45847412 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 October 2018 |accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref>
